\contentsline {subsection}{Replaced: \truncate {.3\textwidth }{ (i.e.\ southward IMF at Earth and Mercury), the magnetic field varies significantly across the magnetopause boundary, on spatial scales comparable to a typical ion gyroradius. Under such conditions the frozen-in field theorem of Section\nobreakspace {}\ref {intro:sec:frozenin} breaks down, and conditions are favourable for reconnection of the two magnetic fields as they diffuse and mix in a region across the dayside magnetopause. At Earth it is well established that dayside reconnection is more efficient under such conditions, although still occurs to a lesser extent when the IMF is directed northward \citep [e.g.][]{eastwood2015}. At the outer planets this relationship is less certain (noting that at Jupiter and Saturn a northward IMF would theoretically produce conditions most favourable to reconnection due to the opposite orientation of the planetary dipole). Results of MHD modelling of Saturn's magnetosphere from \citet {jia2012b} suggest dayside reconnection associated with the Dungey cycle occurs especially when the IMF is oriented northward or in the Parker spiral orientation rather than in a southward orientation. However the authors find that overall the large-scale structure of Saturn's magnetosphere is more significantly affected by the solar wind dynamic pressure than the IMF orientation. \citet {masters2015} used an analytical modelling approach to show that while the IMF orientation did significantly influence dayside reconnection at Saturn, overall the dynamics of the outer magnetosphere were likely to be dominated by internal processes. At Jupiter, \citet {kivelson2003} observed a correlation between Jupiter's magnetopause location and the IMF orientation, suggesting that during a period of northward IMF orientation, dayside reconnection caused the displacement of the magnetopause boundary inward towards the planet.}}{18}{figure.caption.5}
