\contentsline {subsection}{Added: \truncate {.3\textwidth }{The UCL/AGA model is implemented in \textit {Matlab}. To create a model output, the user provides a magnetodisc radius $R_\mathrm {D}$ determining the size of the model grid, and also makes a choice of how the hot plasma population is parameterised, either via a single $K_\mathrm {H}$ value or another parameterisation as described in Chapter\nobreakspace {}\ref {chap:LTsectors}. With equatorial boundary conditions of plasma properties built in as described above, the UCL/AGA model then calculates estimates of plasma properties and magnetic field values across a semi-circular 2-D grid in $r, \mu $ space, with $r$ ranging from \SI {1}{R_S} to the chosen value of $R_\mathrm {D}$, and $\mu =\qopname \relax o{cos}{\theta }$ the cosine of colatitude ranging from -1 to 1. A single model calculation takes ${\sim }$\SI {5}{\second } to run locally for a small dayside model, but can take up to ${\sim }$\SI {100}{\second } for a large nightside model where a smaller value of $\gamma $ and therefore a much higher number of iterations is required before the model achieves convergence. The UCL/AGA model was initially constructed at UCL by Nick Achilleos, Patrick Guio and Chris Arridge, as per \citet {achilleos2010a}. The main changes that I personally implemented were the updates to the temperature and angular velocity boundary conditions using results from \citet {wilson2017}; the updated calculations of the `shielding field' component; and the hot plasma parameterisations for different local time sectors, as described later in this thesis.}}{33}{figure.caption.7}
